In the last 25 years I have build and run multiple distributed software engineering organisations.
My management style/philosophy is based on a couple of core believes &hellip;
 The Power of Why - I like to lead with Why (to make sure Talent and Passion can meet a Purpose) People first - I always think and feel that people are the solution (not the problem) Heterogenerity for the win - You have to be different to complement each other (and to create innovation) No surprises - Everybody (at all times) should be clear on what is happening and why it is happening, which leads to &hellip; Building and maintain trust (and respect) (between the people) at all cost!

Everybody is talking about Kotlin. Me too!!!
Obviously the question is: Is Kotlin the next better thing?
Is Kotlin going to replace Java? Is Kotlin going to replace Scala? Is Kotlin the next better language that will make Software Engineers (much) more productive?
To find out I ported my Scala Advent of Code solutions to Kotlin.
My main take aways are &hellip;
 if you know Java, learning Kotlin will be easier and faster than learning Scala Kotlin is without a doubt &ldquo;the better Java&rdquo;  it compiles fast it runs fast it has very good tooling/IDE support (namely (obviously) the support in Intellij is first-class) it runs on Android hell &hellip; it even runs on Raspberry Pi with Arrows it has a very nice (pure) functional programming library   if you know Scala, learning Kotlin will be even easier, but you will also feel that you are not gaining anything or even that you are loosing some capabilities that are valuable  Sooooo &hellip; my exec summary is &hellip;

The other day I was explaining again how to build an MVP and I was using the skateboard picture (again :)).
